<p>
General form of Volterra equation is \( \phi(x) u(x)=f(x)+\lambda \int_{0}^{x} K(x, t) u(t) d t \)
</p>

<p>
    If \( \phi(x)=1 \) then \( \phi(x) u(x)=f(x)+\lambda \int_{0}^{x} K(x, t) u(t) d t \rightarrow \text { 2nd kind } \)
</p>

<p>
    If \(\phi(x)=0\), then \(u(x)=f(x)+\lambda \int_{a}^{x} K(x, t) u(t) d t \rightarrow \text { 1st kind }\)
</p>

<p>
    The first kind Volterra equations is usually written as
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( f(x)=\int_{0}^{x} K(x, t) u(t) d t \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(3.2)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The relation between first kind and second kind of equations can be established in
the following manner. If the derivatives <span class="l-example">\( \frac{d f}{d x}=f^{\prime}(x), \frac{\partial K}{\partial x}=K_{x}(x, t)\) and \(\frac{\partial K}{\partial t} K_{t}(x, t) \)</span> exist and continuous, the equation of first kind can be reduced to equation of second kind in two ways.
</p>

<p>
<b>The first and simple way</b>: is to differentiate (3.1) with respect to x and we obtain the equation by using Leibnitz rule
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( K(x, x) u(x)+\int_{0}^{x} K_{x}(x, t) u(t) d t=f^{\prime}(x) \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(3.3)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If \( K(x, x) \cancel{=} 0 \), then dividing throughout by this we obtain
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( u(x)+\int_{0}^{x} \frac{K_{x}(x, t)}{K(x, x)} u(t) d t=\frac{f^{\prime}(x)}{K(x, x)} \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(3.4)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
and the reduction is accomplished.
</p>

<p>
The second way to obtain 2<sup>nd</sup> kind of Volterra equation from 1st kind is by using integration by parts, if we set \( \int_{0}^{x} u(t) d t=\phi(x) \) or equivalently
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( \int_{0}^{x} u(\xi) d \xi=\phi(t) \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(3.5)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
We obtain the equation by parts.
</p>

<p>
<div class="l-example">
\( \left.\left[K(x, t) \int_{0}^{t} u(\xi) d \xi\right]\right|_{t=0} ^{x}-\int_{0}^{x} K_{t}(x, t)\left(\int_{0}^{t} u(\xi) d \xi\right) d t=f(x) \)
</div>
</p>

<p>
which reduces to \( \left.K(x, t) \phi(t)\right|_{t=0} ^{x}-\int_{0}^{x} K_{t}(x, t) \phi(t) d t=f(x) \)
</p>

<p>
and finally we get,
</p>

<p>
<div class="l-example">
\( K(x, x) \phi(x)-K(x, 0) \cdot \phi(0)-\int_{0}^{x} K_{t}(x, t) \phi(t) d t=f(x) \)
</div>
</p>

<p>
It is obvious that \( \phi(0)=0 \), and dividing out by \( K(x , x) \).
</p>

<p>
We have <span class="l-example">\( \phi(x)=\left\{\frac{f(x)}{K(x, x)}\right\}+\int_{0}^{x}\left\{\frac{K_{t}(x, t)}{K(x, x)}\right\} \phi(t) d t \)</span>,
</p>

<p>
    <div class="l-example">
    \( \phi(x)=F(x)+\int_{0}^{x} G(x, t) \phi(t) d t, \frac{f(x)}{K(x, x)}=F(x), \frac{K_{t}(x, t)}{K(x, x)}=G(x, t) \)
    </div>
</p>


<div class="red bold">Example 3.7:</div>
<p>
Reduce the equation of Volterra 1<sup>st</sup> kind \( e^{x}=1+\int_{0}^{x} e^{x+t} u(t) d t \) by using Leibnitz rule.
</p>

<div class="red bold">Solution 3.5:</div>

<p>
Differentiating both sides by using Leibnitz rule;
</p>

<p>
    <div class="l-example">
    \( e^{x}=1 . e^{2 x} u(x)+\int_{0}^{x} e^{x+t} u(t) d t \Rightarrow u(x)=e^{-x}-\int_{0}^{x} e^{t-x} u(t) d t \)
    </div>
</p>

<p>
<b>Laplace Transforms Rule:</b>
</p>
<p>
Laplace Transformations of the some of the functions;
</p>

<p>
<div class="l-example">
\( L\{u(x)\}=\int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-s x} u(x) d x \)
</div>
</p>

<ol>
<li>\( L\{a\}=\frac{a}{s}, \quad a, b \in R \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{x^{n}\right\}=\frac{n !}{s^{n+1}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{e^{-a t}\right\}=\frac{1}{s+a} \)</li>
<li>\( L\{\sin a t\}=\frac{a}{s^{2}+a^{2}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\{\cos a t\}=\frac{s}{s^{2}+a^{2}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{t . e^{-a t}\right\}=\frac{1}{(s+a)^{2}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{t^{n} . e^{-a t}\right\}=\frac{n !}{(s+a)^{n+1}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{e^{-a t} . \sin b t\right\}=\frac{b}{(s+a)^{2}+b^{2}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{e^{-a t} . \cos b t\right\}=\frac{s+a}{(s+a)^{2}+b^{2}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{\frac{e^{-a t}-e^{-b t}}{b-a}\right\}=\frac{1}{(s+a)(s+b)} \)</li>
<li>\( L\left\{\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi x}}\right\}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{s}} \)</li>
<li>\( L\{2 \sqrt{\frac{t}{\pi}}\}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{s^{3}}} \)</li>
</ol>